ing on the interactions of medicine, mysticism and reproduction as a feminist project, the author explores the ontology of female flesh; the productive use of pain, suffering and sickness; and the ethics of a maternal theology based on the melancholic and surrogate activities that underlie Kempe's experience. Structured broadly via a traverse through the life course, the book shows how Kempe'sresponse to suffering is illuminated by the medieval medical discourse by which she is contemporaneously read, and by which she engineers her own construction and understanding of self. It also explores Kempe's persistent attendance to her mystical body and refusal to compromise her instinct to authentically show how she feels. LAURA KALAS is a Lecturer in Medieval Literature at Swansea University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezEnglandxHistory. 0aMedicine, MedievalzEngland. 0aMysticismzEnglandvEarly works to 1800. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChrist the Physician.  afeminist.  ainterdisciplinary study.  amaternal theology.  amedical discourse.  amedical humanities.  amedieval.  amysticism.  aontology.  aspirituality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446878?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446878423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446878/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles